00:00:06,130 --> 00:00:08,850
The first is nowcasting.

4
00:00:08,850 --> 00:00:11,520
Traditionally what people have done is forecasting.

5
00:00:11,520 --> 00:00:13,980
You collect a bunch of data, you build a model,

6
00:00:13,980 --> 00:00:17,010
and you use that model to predict the future.

7
00:00:17,010 --> 00:00:19,950
With nowcasting, you collect a lot of data

8
00:00:19,950 --> 00:00:21,710
and you build a model, but instead you

9
00:00:21,710 --> 00:00:24,070
use it to predict what's happening now.

10
00:00:24,070 --> 00:00:27,150
So the example we're going to use is Google Flu trends.

11
00:00:27,150 --> 00:00:29,050
The way that traditionally we determine

12
00:00:29,050 --> 00:00:30,990
that there's an outbreak of the flu

13
00:00:30,990 --> 00:00:33,760
is when someone's ill they go to the doctor,

14
00:00:33,760 --> 00:00:35,570
the doctor fills out an incident report

15
00:00:35,570 --> 00:00:38,910
and passes that on to their local health department, which

16
00:00:38,910 --> 00:00:42,950
then passes it up the hierarchy through the county, the state.

17
00:00:42,950 --> 00:00:44,450
Eventually it reaches the Centers

18
00:00:44,450 --> 00:00:47,812
for Disease Control in Atlanta, Georgia.

19
00:00:47,812 --> 00:00:49,270
That process takes about two weeks,

20
00:00:49,270 --> 00:00:51,540
so it takes a roughly two weeks to know that there's

21
00:00:51,540 --> 00:00:54,090
an outbreak of flu, by which time

22
00:00:54,090 --> 00:00:56,766
the outbreak may actually already be over.

