00:00:56,766 --> 00:00:59,680
With Google Flu Trends, what Google did is

24
00:00:59,680 --> 00:01:02,460
they started with lots of data.

25
00:01:02,460 --> 00:01:07,155
From 2003 to 2008, they looked at weekly search queries.

26
00:01:07,155 --> 00:01:09,890
There's about 50 million of these.

27
00:01:09,890 --> 00:01:11,710
From the search queries, they were

28
00:01:11,710 --> 00:01:16,220
able to derive 45 terms that were relevant to people

29
00:01:16,220 --> 00:01:18,500
who are searching for flu information

30
00:01:18,500 --> 00:01:21,300
when they had the flu.

31
00:01:21,300 --> 00:01:23,350
They used this to build a model.

32
00:01:23,350 --> 00:01:25,620
The model was very accurate.

33
00:01:25,620 --> 00:01:28,710
In February of 2010 it was able to detect an outbreak

34
00:01:28,710 --> 00:01:32,550
two weeks ahead of CDC data.

35
00:01:32,550 --> 00:01:36,040
Initially the model was about 97% accurate,

36
00:01:36,040 --> 00:01:38,776
but during the period from 2011 to 2013,

37
00:01:38,776 --> 00:01:42,860
it overestimated the prevalence of flu,

38
00:01:42,860 --> 00:01:46,130
